#. (itstool) path: div/p
#: Source/Guidelines/en/CC-LanguageCorpora.xml:150
msgid ""
"Header information which relates to the whole corpus rather than to "
"individual components of it should be factored out and included in the <_:"
"gi-1/> element prefixed to the whole. This two-level structure allows for "
"contextual information to be specified at the corpus level, at the "
"individual text level, or at both. Discussion of the kinds of information "
"which may thus be specified is provided below, in section <_:ptr-2/>, as "
"well as in chapter <_:ptr-3/>. Information of this type should in general be "
"specified only once: a variety of methods are provided for associating it "
"with individual components of a corpus, as further described in section <_:"
"ptr-4/>."
msgstr ""

#. (itstool) path: div/p
#: Source/Guidelines/en/CC-LanguageCorpora.xml:161
msgid ""
"In some cases, the design of a corpus is reflected in its internal "
"structure. For example, a corpus of newspaper extracts might be arranged to "
"combine all stories of one type (reportage, editorial, reviews, etc.) into "
"some higher-level grouping, possibly with sub-groups for date, region, etc. "
"The <_:gi-1/> element provides no direct support for reflecting such "
"internal corpus structure in the markup: it treats the corpus as an "
"undifferentiated series of components, each tagged <_:gi-2/>."
msgstr ""

#. (itstool) path: div/p
#: Source/Guidelines/en/CC-LanguageCorpora.xml:170
msgid ""
"If it is essential to reflect a single permanent organization of a corpus "
"into sub- and sub-sub-corpora, then the corpus or the high-level subcorpora "
"may be encoded as composite texts, using the <_:gi-1/> element described "
"below and in section <_:ptr-2/>. The mechanisms for corpus characterization "
"described in this chapter, however, are designed to reduce the need to do "
"this. Useful groupings of components may easily be expressed using the text "
"classification and identification elements described in section <_:ptr-3/>, "
"and those for associating declarations with corpus components described in "
"section <_:ptr-4/>. These methods also allow several different methods of "
"text grouping to co-exist, each to be used as needed at different times. "
"This helps minimize the danger of cross-classification and misclassification "
"of samples, and helps improve the flexibility with which parts of a corpus "
"may be characterized for different applications."
msgstr ""

#. (itstool) path: div/p
#: Source/Guidelines/en/CC-LanguageCorpora.xml:186
msgid ""
"Anthologies and collections are often treated as texts in their own right, "
"if only for historical reasons. In conventional publishing, at least, "
"anthologies are published as units, with single editorial responsibility and "
"common front and back matter which may need to be included in their "
"electronic encodings. The texts collected in the anthology, of course, may "
"also need to be identifiable as distinct individual objects for study."
msgstr ""

#. (itstool) path: div/p
#: Source/Guidelines/en/CC-LanguageCorpora.xml:194
msgid ""
"Poem cycles, epistolary novels, and epistolary essays differ from "
"anthologies in that they are often written as single works, by single "
"authors, for single occasions; nevertheless, it can be useful to treat their "
"constituent parts as individual texts, as well as the cycle itself. "
"Structurally, therefore, they may be treated in the same way as anthologies: "
"in both cases, the body of the text is composed largely of other texts."
msgstr ""

#. (itstool) path: div/p
#: Source/Guidelines/en/CC-LanguageCorpora.xml:202
